{"metadata":{"objective":"Basic probability","lastStepAudioPath":"summary","audioPath":"D1/6/Refresher"},"steps":[{"headerText":"","leftText":"<p><span class=\"ju-cktitle\" style=\"color:#025B5B;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:bold;\">Selecting the first few committee members</span><br /><br />Everyone at the office is really excited about the annual company summer picnic!<br /><br />You&#39;re in charge this year and you have to pick a committee of 6 of your colleagues to help you plan the day.&nbsp; There are 12 volunteers who want to be on the committee.<br /><br />Last year, there was some grumbling about the way the planning committee was selected, so this year you&#39;re considering picking committee members randomly so that everyone will feel the process is fair.<br /><br />You want to be fair, but you also want to make sure you&#39;ve got a good mix of people who will plan&nbsp;a great party.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br /><br />What are the chances that random selection will give you the mix of people you want?<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img alt=\"The sign up sheet for picnic volunteers.  Employees have listed their names, job titles, and the number of picnics attended.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","settings":{"showHeader":0,"showAudio":1,"audioPath":"1","hideRightPanel":0,"showNext":1,"delayStep":"0","delayRight":"0"}},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"2"},"leftText":"<p>Before getting into the committee selections, first look at a few basic probability examples.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":null,"headerText":"Probability basics"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"3"},"leftText":"<p>There are 10 marbles in a bag.<br /><br />4 of the marbles are blue and 6 of the marbles are red.<br /><br /><span style=\"line-height: 20.8px;\">If you reach into the bag and remove a marble without looking, which one of the two colors is more likely to be selected?</span><br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":"The basics of probability"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"4"},"leftText":"<p>Since there are more red marbles, it is more likely that you will select a red marble, but how likely is it that you will select a red on the first try?<br /><br />This is what the probability will tell you.<br /><br />You can write the probability of selecting a red marble on the first try as P(red).<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p>Probability of selecting red on the first try = P(red)</p><p>P(red) is more likely than P(blue)</p><p>What is P(red)?</p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"5"},"leftText":"<p><br />You can write the probability that a specific outcome will happen as a fraction.<br /><br />1.&nbsp; Count the number of ways a&nbsp;specific outcome can happen<br /><br />2.&nbsp; Count the number of ways all possible outcomes can happen.<br /><br />3.&nbsp; Write the probability fraction as shown on the right.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Probability fraction:</span><br />&nbsp;</p><p>`&quot;number of ways a&nbsp;SPECIFIC outcome can happen&quot;/&quot;number of ways ALL outcomes can happen&quot;`</p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"6"},"leftText":"<p>The specific outcome that interests you is the selection of a red marble.<br /><br />Since there are 6 red marbles, the number of ways the specific outcome can happen is 6.<br /><br />6 is the numerator of the fraction.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"The marble bag has 4 blue marbles and 6 red marbles. The number of ways the specific outcome of selecting a red marble can occur is 6, so 6 goes in the top or numerator of the probability fraction.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"7"},"leftText":"<p>Since there are 10 marbles in the bag, there are 10 possible ways that any&nbsp;marble could be selected.<br /><br />This means that the number of all possible outcomes is 10, so the denominator of the fraction is 10.<br /><br />You have a 6 out of 10 chance of selecting a red marble.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"10 goes in the bottom or denominator of the probability fraction.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"8"},"leftText":"<p>Now that you have found probability as a fraction, you can convert it to a percentage.<br /><br />Use a calculator to divide the numerator by the&nbsp;denominator to&nbsp;change the fraction to a decimal.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p>P(red) = `6/10`</p><p>`6divide10=0.6`</p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"9"},"leftText":"<p>Move the decimal point 2 places to the right and write the % symbol to convert it to a percentage.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"The decimal point in zero point six zero moves one place to the right of the six, and a second place to the right of the zero to equal sixty percent.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p><p>Note:&nbsp; Since there is only one digit showing to the right of the decimal point, add a zero before moving the decimal point.</p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"10"},"leftText":"<p>The probability that you will select a red marble is 6 out of 10.<br /><br />P(red) = `6/10` or 0.6&nbsp;or 60%<br /><br />There is a 60% chance you will select a red marble on the first try.&nbsp; You have a slightly better chance of &nbsp;randomly selecting a red marble than you do of randomly selecting a blue marble.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"Since 60% is between 50% and 100%, it is more likely to happen.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"11"},"leftText":"<p>Tomorrow, you are meeting with all of the volunteers to announce which of them will be on the planning committee.<br /><br />Tonight, you write all of the volunteers&#39; names on separate index cards, shuffle them, and place them face down.<br /><br />Then you randomly pick the cards to see what actually happens.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img alt=\"\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":"Back to the committee selection"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"12"},"leftText":"<p>You think it will be valuable to have someone on the committee who attended the annual picnic several times in the past.<br /><br />You wonder if you can choose an experienced person on the first pick.<br /><br />As a percentage, what is the probability that your first pick will be someone who attended the picnic at least 7 times?<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p>What is P(7 or more times)?</p><p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"13"},"leftText":"<p>You count the number of volunteers who attended the picnic at least 7 times.&nbsp; There are 6 of them:<br /><br />Amira, Elana, Jasmine, Nadia, Rajeev, and Sara<br /><br />You know that there are 12 volunteers.<br /><br />Of the 12 volunteers, there are 6 volunteers who attended the picnic at least 7 times.<br /><br />This means you have a 6 out of 12 chance of picking the name of someone who attended the picnic at least 7 times in the past.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"Table of 12 picnic committee volunteers.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /><br /><span class=\"ju-small-examples\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:tahoma;font-size:14px;\"><a href=\"S3_BUCKET_/QS8/3/Tableof12picniccommitteevolunteers_atleast7.html\" onclick=\"window.open(this.href, 'Picnic_committee_volunteers', 'resizable=yes,status=no,location=no,toolbar=no,menubar=no,fullscreen=no,scrollbars=no,dependent=yes,width=400,left=100,height=500,top=50'); Instead, you decide to find the probability that you&#39;ll select someone who attended the picnic just a few times.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"Since 50% is exactly in the middle between 0% and 100%, it is equally likely to happen as not happen.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":""},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"16"},"leftText":"<p>You also notice that quite a few of the volunteers on the list are from the customer service department.<br /><br />What is the probability that the first volunteer selected will be from customer service and also attended the picnic 5 times or less?<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p>What is P(customer service and 5 or fewer times) ?</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","headerText":"What are the chances of  picking someone who attended the picnic a few times?"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"17"},"leftText":"<p>There are 4 volunteers from customer service, but only 2 of them attended the picnic 5 or fewer times:<br /><br />Danielle and Victoria<br /><br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"Table of 12 picnic committee volunteers. Danielle from Customer Service attended the picnic 5 times, and Victoria from Customer Service attended 4 times.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"18"},"leftText":"<p>Make the probability fraction, then change it to a percentage by dividing and moving the decimal point 2 places to the right. &nbsp;Round the division to 4 decimal places.<br /><br />There are 2 ways that the outcome of being in customer service and attending 5 or fewer times can happen.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br /><br />There are 12 possible outcomes.<br />&nbsp;</p><table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-powertip\" style=\"width:500px\"><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\">DID YOU KNOW?&nbsp; return false;\">Rounding review: Picture it!</a></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p>P(customer service and 5 or fewer times) =`2/12`</p><p>`2divide12=0.1667`</p><p>`0.1667 = 16.67%`</p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"19"},"leftText":"<p>The probability that the first volunteer selected is from customer service and attended the picnic 5 or fewer times is 16.67%.<br /><br />This is not very likely.</p><p><br /><br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"Since 16.6 7% is between 0% and 50%, it is less likely to happen.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":""},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"20"},"leftText":"<p>After looking at these probabilities, you&#39;re not so sure that picking the names randomly is going to give you the mix of people on the committee you would like.&nbsp; You decide to draw the names anyway to see what will happen.<br /><br />You randomly select two cards and pick Danielle and Tony.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img alt=\"Danielle attended the picnic 5 times, and Tony attended 6 times.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":"What happens to the chances once you've picked some names?"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":"0","delayRight":"0","audioPath":"21"},"leftText":"<p>You notice that Danielle attended the picnic 5 times.&nbsp; You look back at your list and see that there are several others who attended the picnic 5 times.<br /><br />You wonder how likely it is that you will pick another person who attended the picnic exactly 5 times.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p>What is P(attended 5 times) ?</p><p>&nbsp;</p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":"0","delayRight":0,"audioPath":"22"},"leftText":"<p>There are 3 volunteers remaining who attended the picnic 5 times.<br /><br />Carlos, Guy, and Lisa<br /><br />You already selected Danielle and Tony so there are only 10 volunteers left.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"Table of picnic committee volunteers.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":""},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":"0","delayRight":"0","audioPath":"23"},"leftText":"<p>Since there are 3 volunteers remaining who attended the picnic 5 times, there are 3 ways that this outcome can happen.<br /><br />Since there are 10 names left, there are 10 possible outcomes.<br /><br />The chances of picking someone who attended 5 times are 3 out of 10.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p>P(attended 5 times) =`3/10`</p><p>`3divide10 = 0.3`</p><p>`0.3 = 0.30 = 30%`</p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":"0","delayRight":0,"audioPath":"24"},"leftText":"<p>After Danielle and Tony are selected, the probability that the next volunteer selected attended the picnic 5 times is not very likely since there is only a 30% chance that this will happen.<br /><br />You think this is a good thing since you are hoping to get a variety of opinions about how to make the picnic a success!<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"Since 30% is between 0% and 50%, it is less likely to happen.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>"}],"overviewHeader":"Overview"}
